# GD32 FOC Project Rules

## Code Style & Naming
- Functions: `Module_FunctionName` (e.g. `Timer1_Init`, `PWM_SetDutyCycle`)
- Macros: `UPPERCASE_WITH_UNDERSCORES`
- Types: `xxx_t` suffix
- Follow existing patterns unless refactoring
- Prefer functional semantic names at upper layers (L1/L2/L3) instead of direct peripheral names (e.g. avoid `Usart1`/`Timer1` in abstraction APIs).
- For unavoidable cross-layer shared params/callbacks/enums, define them in a dedicated shared header rather than exposing level-2 module types directly in platform API headers.

## Brace Style (Allman Style)
- **Braces must occupy their own line, never on the same line as statements**
- Correct:
```c
void Function(void)
{
    if (condition)
    {
        // code
    }
}
```
- Incorrect:
```c
void Function(void) {
    if (condition) {
        // code
    }
}
```

## Module Boundaries
- Each `Utilities/*` module is self-contained
- Clean API via header files
- Avoid cross-module globals
- Dependency layering uses: `LS` config → `L1` orchestration → `L2` service/protocol → `L3` algorithm → `L41` math → `L42` PAL → `L5` board drivers
- `L1/L2/L3` may access `L5` only through `L42_PAL`
- `L5` must not depend on `L1/L2/L3`

## Header Include Policy
- For non-self-contained modules, place primary dependency includes in the corresponding `.h` file instead of scattering them in `.c` files.
- `.c` files should prefer including only their module header; add extra includes in `.c` only for unavoidable cyclic-dependency or implementation-private cases.
- The goal is to keep dependency structure visible at header level for architecture review and portability.
- Public headers in L2/L3 must not include `Utilities/*` headers directly; expose them via special-layer wrappers.

## Priority & Source of Truth
- **Primary source**: actual code (`.c/.h` files) is authoritative
- Secondary reference: documentation under `docs/`
- Rules in `docs/engineering/dev-guidelines/rules/*` guide AI and collaboration

## Editable Scope
- ✅ `foc/src`, `foc/include`
- ✅ `examples/GD32F303_FOCExplore/software/Application/**`
- ✅ `examples/GD32F303_FOCExplore/software/Utilities/**`
- ✅ Docs: `docs/`, `NEXT_MISSION.md`, `CHANGELOG.md`
- ❌ Do not edit by default: `Firmware/**`, `.eide/**` (exceptions only for build/flash fixes)

## Interrupt Handling
- Keep ISRs short and deterministic
- Avoid blocking in ISRs; if unavoidable, ensure it cannot affect real-time behavior
- Prefer ISR forwarding to module handler functions for complex logic

## Timing & Scheduling
- Use task slots defined by configuration macros in `control_scheduler.c`
- Use DWT timing for execution measurement
- Initialize timers via parameterized APIs (Timer1/Timer2/PWM)

## Execution Time & Control-Period Budget
- Ensure each control task completes well under its configured period
- Use `ControlScheduler_EnableDWT()` / `ControlScheduler_GetExecutionCycles()` to validate
- Avoid blocking delays (`delay_*()`) in initialization/calibration paths unless necessary
- If blocking delays are used, document execution time impact and ensure no interference with real-time tasks

## Safety
- Always include `<stddef.h>` when using `NULL`
- Do not change clocks or memory mapping without mission-level approval
- Preserve existing hardware configuration unless change is explicitly required

## Build & Flash
- Primary development entry: VS Code + EIDE extension (build/flash/debug)
- Compilation backend: Keil μVision 5 + ARM Compiler 5 (AC5)
- Flash/debug: ST-LINK (AI may execute tooling commands when user-requested; hardware behavior judgment and acceptance remain user-owned)
- Warning policy: do not introduce new warnings; if legacy warnings exist, document cause/mitigation and convergence plan

## Iteration & Documentation Contract
- Only consider a change a new iteration when user explicitly requests "进行下一次迭代"
- After each iteration, update:
  - `CHANGELOG.md` (version history)
  - `NEXT_MISSION.md` (next iteration goals)
  - `docs/` (architecture/guide updates)
  - Rules (if workflow or architecture changed)
